## Async Waterfalls vs Parallel Fetches

### What a waterfall is
In web performance, a **waterfall** is when requests are made one after another instead of concurrently. Each request waits for the previous one to complete before starting.

```
Waterfall (sequential):
|--- request A (300ms) ---|
                          |--- request B (400ms) ---|
                                                    |--- request C (250ms) ---|
Total: 950ms

Parallel:
|--- request A (300ms) ---|
|--- request B (400ms) -------|
|--- request C (250ms) ---|
Total: 400ms (max)
```

For 3 requests totaling 950ms, parallelism saves 550ms — a 58% improvement.

### Why sequential await creates a waterfall
`await` suspends the function execution until the promise settles. Each subsequent `await` cannot start until the previous one completes:

```js
async function load() {
  const a = await fetchA();   // function pauses here (300ms)
  const b = await fetchB();   // function pauses here (400ms)
  const c = await fetchC();   // function pauses here (250ms)
  return { a, b, c };         // runs at 950ms
}
```

### Promise.all for parallel execution
`Promise.all(promises)` starts all promises immediately and returns a new promise that resolves with an array of results:

```js
async function load() {
  const [a, b, c] = await Promise.all([
    fetchA(),  // starts immediately — request in flight
    fetchB(),  // starts immediately — request in flight
    fetchC(),  // starts immediately — request in flight
  ]);
  // all three in flight simultaneously
  // total time = max(300, 400, 250) = 400ms
  return { a, b, c };
}
```

`fetchA()` without `await` starts the request and returns a Promise. Passing promises to `Promise.all` lets them race — whichever resolves last determines the total wait time.

### The key insight: fetch starts requests immediately
```js
// These start requests at the same time:
const p1 = fetch('/api/a');  // request starts NOW
const p2 = fetch('/api/b');  // request starts NOW
const p3 = fetch('/api/c');  // request starts NOW

// These start them one at a time:
const r1 = await fetch('/api/a');  // wait until done
const r2 = await fetch('/api/b');  // only now starts
const r3 = await fetch('/api/c');  // only now starts
```

### Two correct parallel patterns
```js
// Pattern 1: Promise.all (idiomatic, concise)
const [a, b, c] = await Promise.all([fetchA(), fetchB(), fetchC()]);

// Pattern 2: Start then await (more verbose, same performance)
const pa = fetchA();
const pb = fetchB();
const pc = fetchC();
const a = await pa;
const b = await pb;
const c = await pc;
```

Both are equivalent in performance. `Promise.all` is preferred because it groups related concurrent operations explicitly.

### When sequential IS correct
Sequence requests when later requests depend on earlier results:

```js
// Correct sequential — B needs A's result:
const user = await fetchUser(userId);        // must come first
const posts = await fetchPosts(user.team);   // uses user.team

// Partially parallel — B and C need A but not each other:
const user = await fetchUser(userId);
const [posts, settings] = await Promise.all([
  fetchPosts(user.team),      // uses user.team
  fetchSettings(user.orgId),  // uses user.orgId
]);
```

### Diagnosing waterfalls
In browser DevTools → Network tab → select 'Waterfall' view. Requests that start after the previous one's bar ends are sequential. Requests whose bars overlap start concurrently.

Red flags in code:
```js
// These are ALWAYS sequential (each awaits before the next fetch starts):
const a = await fetch(urlA).then(r => r.json());
const b = await fetch(urlB).then(r => r.json());
const c = await fetch(urlC).then(r => r.json());
```

### You just learned
Sequential `await` creates a waterfall — each request waits for the previous one to complete. For independent requests, use `Promise.all([...])` to run them concurrently. Total time = slowest request, not the sum. Always ask 'does request B need data from request A?' before sequencing.
